Pronunciation: aˈda gəˈmaŋtajŋ ~ aˈda gəˈmantajŋ ~ aˈda gaˈmaŋtajŋ ~ aˈda gaˈmantajŋ

Borrowed_Word: Austronesian borrowing. First element ‹ai-› is certainly a reflex of PMP *kahiw ‘tree, wood’ (ACD).
Austronesian, cf. PMP *beli 'buy, value, price; marriage prestations, brideprice; purchase' (ACD). Probably a South or Southeast Sulawesi language like Buton ‹ali› 'buy'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *beli 'buy, value, price; marriage prestations, brideprice; purchase' (ACD). Probably a South or Southeast Sulawesi language, e.g., Layolo ‹ali› 'price'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *qahelu 'pestle' (ACD). Possible source languages for this borrowing can be found on all sides of Alor, e.g., Tokodede, Erai, Alorese ‹alu› 'pestle'.
Austronesian Timor, cf. Tokodede ‹luli›, Erai ‹luli›. Initial /a/ could be prosthetic or might suggest borrowing of a causative marked form reflecting *pa-luli.

Ultimately from Tamil ‹pāṉai› ‘large earthen pot or vessel’, but intermediate sources unknown; not found in modern Malay. The loss of initial /p/ suggests the same intermediary as that for other borrowed roots with initial /a/, believed to be reflecting original PMP *pa-.

First element ane- possible Austronesian borrowing, cf. PMP *anay 'termite, white ant' (ACD). The origin of the second element is unknown, but is also found in other Alor languages, e.g., Abui ‹anakaai› 'termite, white ant'.
Second element -es is likely a borrowing of Timor Austronesian, e.g., Tokodede ‹ecu›, Tetun ‹etu› 'rice, food, sustenance'
Possible Timorese Austronesian borrowing, e.g., Tokodede ‹rose› 'rub, scrape'. Initial /a/ may be prothetic to avoid an initial /r/.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *ribut 'storm' (ACD). Initial /a/ may be prothetic to avoid an initial /r/.

Paradigm: narudi, arudi, garudi, tarudi, nyarudi, yarudi

Borrowed_Word: Wersing arus 'deer' from Austronesian, cf. PWMP *uRsa 'deer' (ACD). Initial /a/ could be prosthetic. Immediate source may be Malay ‹rusa› 'deer'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *qasiRa 'salt' (ACD). Presence of initial /a/ suggests borrowing from an early Austronesian language no longer extent.
Possibly from Sanskrit ‹lakṣa› 'hundred thousand', via Malay ‹laksa›. Intermediate sources unknown. Alternative sources may be eastern Sulawesi languages, e.g., Sula ‹saka› '100'.

Paradigm: natok, atok, gatok, tatok, nyatok, yatok

Borrowed_Word: Austronesian borrowing, likely reflecting compound of reflexes of PMP *kahiw 'tree, wood’ (ACD) plus PCMP *koli 'Borassus sundaicus' (Verheijen 1984:47). The initial part of the form is unusual and may indicate the borrowing is from Kisar ‹au› 'tree, wood'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *kawil 'fish hook' (ACD). Plausible sources in the area have not been identified.
Malay ‹baju› 'shirt'.
Tetun ‹bali› 'to treat , to cure , to give or apply a remedy, to take care of (including to keep animals)'
Tetun ‹bainaka› 'guest'. Unexplained metathesis /i/ and /n/ in Wersing.
Malay ‹pasar› 'market' via Tetun ‹basar› 'market'.
Malay ‹pahat› 'chisel' via Tetun ‹bahat› 'chisel'.

Pronunciation: ˈbat ˈbloiŋ ~ ˈbat bəˈloiŋ ~ ˈbat boˈloiŋ

Borrowed_Word: Tetun ‹beba|k› 'stalk or stem of a palm frond, used for buiding walls of houses and panels in fences'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *betuŋ 'bamboo of very large diameter, probably Dendrocalamus sp.' (ACD). Possibly from Malay ‹betuŋ› 'elephant bamboo'.
Malay ‹biasa› 'usually'.
West Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Helong ‹biki› 'strong'.

Unknown Austronesian source, combining a cognate of Makasar ‹bila› 'bael, Aegle marmelos' plus a reflex of *kahiw 'tree, wood' (ACD). In Wersing and the other East Alor languages, there was a semantic shift from 'bael' to 'papaya'. Pantar and West Alor languages retain the meaning 'bael'.
Malay ‹bicara› 'to speak'.
Central Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Tokodede, Mambae ‹biti› 'sleeping mat'.

Pronunciation: ˈbloiŋ siˈkɛri ~ bəˈloiŋ siˈkɛri ~ boˈloiŋ siˈkɛri

Borrowed_Word: Austronesian, cf. PMP *bubuŋ 'ridge of the roof; ridge of a mountain, peak; deck of a boat; cover the ridgepole with thatch' (ACD). No known reflexes with approriate semantics in nearby Austronesian languages.
Calqued from Malay ‹ubi kayu› 'cassava', literally 'tree tuber'.
Malay ‹berani› 'brave'.
Malay ‹dagang› 'trade'.
Likely source Buginese ‹ʤaka› ‘comb’ possibly via a Southeast Sulawesi language, e.g., Tolaki ‹daka› ‘comb’. The final /r/ of the Wersing form is unexplained.
Makasar ‹dalang› 'slow, sluggish, lazy'.
Tokodede ‹damat› 'door'.
Central Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Tokodede ‹damu›, Mambae ‹dam ~ damu› 'needle' < PMP *zaRum ‘needle’ (ACD).
Calque of Austronesian Timor use of the lexical item 'name' as a quantifier.
Alorese ‹deko› 'trousers', perhaps ultimately from an Eastern Sulawesi language, e.g., Banggai ‹deŋko› 'trousers, pants'.
Tetun ‹dinela› < Portuguese ‹janela› 'window'.
Malay ‹dinas› < Dutch ‹dienst› 'service'.
Tokodede ‹geresi ~ geresin› used in augmenting numerals. Other Timorese languages have a form such as ‹resi ~ resin›, making Tokodede the only candidate for this borrowing.
Likely calque of Malay ‹mata air› 'spring', literally 'water eye'.

Austronesian, cf. PMP *isi 'flesh (of humans, animals, fruits, tubers); contents; blade of a knife; inhabitants, residents' (ACD). The immediate source of borrowing is not known. The semantic shift of contents to body is commonly associated with reflexes of *isi in Timorese Austronesian languages, e.g., Tokodede ‹isi› 'body, flesh', Hresuk ‹isi|k› 'meat, body', Tetun ‹isi|n› 'body'.

-is < Austronesian, cf. PMP *isi 'flesh (of humans, animals, fruits, tubers); contents; blade of a knife; inhabitants, residents' (ACD); -bak 'body' < Austronesian, cf. PMP *hawak ˈwaist, back of the waistˈ (ACD). The immediate source of borrowing is not known. The same lexical parallelism for 'body' is found in nearby Austronesian languages, e.g., Wetar ‹isir-wewaki› 'body'.
Likely Austronesian, cf. Malay ‹sisik› 'scale of fish'
Likely Austronesian borrowing; Initial element kai- is a reflex of PMP *kahiw 'tree, wood'
Austronesian borrowing, likely reflecting < compound of PMP *kahiw ‘tree, wood’, PMP *kuRis ‘scratch’ (ACD).
Dutch ‹kak huis› 'crap house' via Malay ‹kakus›.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *qalunan 'wooden headrest, pillow'. Probably a corruption of Malay ‹kalang hulu› 'pillow'.
Malay ‹kamar› < Dutch ‹kamer› 'room'.
Alorese ‹kandera› < Portuguese ‹cadeira› 'chair'.
Tetun ‹kafe› < Portuguese ‹café› 'coffee'.
Malay ‹kasar› 'rough, coarse'. Unexplained r > l.
Central Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Tokodede, Mambae ‹kaso› 'bean, pea'.
Likely borrowing of Malay ‹kain› 'cloth'.
Likely borrowing of Tokodede ‹giniu› 'knife'.
Likely borrowing ‹kenari› 'canarium'. The final velar nasal in Wersing is unexplained.
Likely reflects a separate borrowing of a compound with Central Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Tokodede, Mambae ‹kaso› 'bean, pea'.
Certainly borrowed, given the plant is introduced. Possibly related to the widely found name for marongga in south-eastern Indonesia, ‹kelor›.
Dutch konto 'account'.
Malay ‹kota›, ultimately from Sanskrit ‹koṭṭa› 'city'.

Malay ‹kuasa› 'power, force, might, vigor, able, capable, having the ability', ulitmately from Sanskrit ‹vaśa› 'will, wish, desire'. Possible intermediate in South or Southeast Sulawesi, e.g., Tolaki ‹kawasa› 'rich'.
Malay ‹kurang› 'not enough, insufficient; few, less'.
Timor Austronesian, e.g., Tetun baban 'patch, mend', Tetun ka|baban 'concealed, hidden (behind something)'.
Possible borrowing of Tokodede ‹kabu› 'stomach, womb; pregnant'.

General_Comment: The Wersing do not usually eat sago. However, in the past, sago was one of the trading goods brought to Alor by people from Maluku, such as Kisar.

Borrowed_Word: Reanalysis of Malay ‹kelumpang› as bimorphemic, with the final syllable of Malay -pang being equated with Wersing bong 'tree'.
Tokodede ‹kluta ~ kuˈluta› 'skin' < PMP *kulit 'skin, hide, rind, bark' (ACD).
West Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Uab Meto ‹laisona› 'onion', probably via South Sulawesi, e.g., Makasar ‹lasuna›, but ultimately from Sanskrit ‹rasuna›.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *dataR ‘flat, flat or level land’ (ACD). No known nearby language evidencing a reflex of this item and the sound change *d > l.
Reduction of Arabic ‹allah taʔala› likely via a South Sulawesi language, e.g., Makasar ‹alla taʔala› 'god'.
Dutch ‹reken|en› 'count'.

Possible Austronesian borrowing, cf. PMP *leku 'bend, fold, folding part of the body; curl up on the ground, of an animal' (ACD). Known reflexes in Austronesian languages in Timor do not fit well with meaning in Wersing, e.g., Tokodede ‹leku› 'cross legs or arms', ‹k|leku› 'bent, crooked'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *kuRis ‘scratch’ (ACD). Possibly from Tetun ‹kuri› 'to touch lightly, to scratch lightly'.
Possibly from Malay ‹lap› 'wipe' < Dutch ‹lap› 'cleaning cloth'. Final /u/ unexplained.
Likely from Tetun ‹liurai› 'king, royal'.
Malay ‹sayang› 'dear, too bad'.
Timorese Austronesian, cf. Tetun ‹ha|lolo› 'follow'.
West Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Termanu ‹lodo›, Helong ‹lolo› ‘straight’.
Austronesian languages both to the East and West frequently have a term related to this, e.g., Tokodede ‹laku›, Erai ‹laku›, Bungku ‹laku› 'civet'.
Austronesian, cf. PCEMP *madar 'ripe, overripe' (ACD). Possibly from Tokodede ‹mada(sa)› 'ripe, cooked'.
Tetun ‹mama› ‘chew without swallowing’ < PMP *mamaq ‘chew without intending to swallow, as betel nut; premasticate food to give to an infant; premasticated food’ (ACD).
Likely early borrowing of widely found form in Austronesian languages potential PCMP reconstruction *malus 'betel vine'.
Malay ‹meja› 'table' < Portuguese ‹mesa›.
Wersing root of -alar < Austronesian, cf. PMP *layaR 'sail' (ACD). Initial /a/ suggests borrowing of a causative marked form reflecting *pa-layaR, e.g., Kisar ‹walara› 'sail', but may be prothetic.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *muntay 'kind of citrus tree and its fruit' (ACD). Austronesian languages both to the West frequently have a term related to this, e.g., Alorese ‹muda› 'orange'.

Likely originally from a Central Maluku language, e.g., Waru ‹mumumur›, Masarete ‹momol› ‘iron’, from where iron was traded. Nearby languages with the same borrowing lack final /l/ and are unlikely intermediaries, cf. Hresuk ‹mumu›, Erai ‹mumu› 'iron'.
Central Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Kemak ‹muusu›, Tokodede ‹k|mus› ‘kiss, suck’.
Possibly West Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Helong ‹maliʔ›, with metathesis of /k/ and /l/.
Possibly from Timorese Austronesian 'foreigner' words, e.g., Tokodede, Tetun ‹malae› 'foreigner'.
Tokodede ‹lomosa› 'shark', with metathesis of /m/ and /l/.
Likely West Timorese Austronesian, e.g., Helong ‹mana› 'place'.

Austronesian, cf. PMP *ma-nipis 'thinness (of materials)' (ACD). There are no known Austronesian languages in the region that have a reflex of PMP *ma-nipis that retains the stative prefix but where *p is lost and the vowels merge into a single syllable.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *qapuR 'lime, calcium' (ACD). Most likely candidate in the region is Erai ‹aur› 'lime'.
Malay ‹oto› < Dutch ‹auto› 'car'.

Forms ‹pandu› and ‹pandut› are widely found west of Alor for a range of oil-yielding plants used in making torches and/or lamps, including Jatropha eurcaa, Calophytlum inophyllum, Ricinus communis. Perhaps ultimately from Malay, Javanese ‹panjut› 'torch'. Final nasal of Wersing form unexplained.
paki < Malay ‹pakai|an› 'clothes'.
Possibly Austronesian, cf. PMP *babuy 'pig' (ACD).
kutu < PMP *kutu 'head louse' (ACD).
makang < Malay ‹makan› 'eat, food'.
Likely from Malay ‹pinggan›, ultimately from Persian ‹pingān› 'plate, dish'.
Likely from Makasar ‹paŋkuluʔ› 'axe'.
Likely early Austronesian borrowing, cf. PMP *buaq 'fruit; areca palm' (ACD).
mamar < Kupang Malay ‹mamar› 'orchard, garden for trees that yield for a long time'.
Alorese ‹peda› 'machete' < Portuguese ‹espada› 'sword'.
Likely ultimately from Malay ‹batari› ‘sorghum’, but the relevant intermediates are not known, likely languages to the West. Vowels suggest this was a distinct borrowing event to that of pètori.
Likely ultimately from Malay ‹batari› ‘sorghum’, but the relevant intermediates are not known, likely languages to the West. Vowels suggest this was a distinct borrowing event to that of pèter.
Malay ‹ribu› 'thousand'.
Erai ‹ruti› 'monitor lizard'.
Moluccan Malay ‹cakalele›, possibly via a Moluccan trading language such as Geser-Goram.

Widespread loanword extending eastward from Javanese ‹salaka› 'silver' and Malay ‹selaka› 'silver', ultimately from Sanskrit ‹chalaka› 'delusive' according to Gonda (1973). Possible intermediate source languages are found on all sides of Alor, e.g., Makasar, Bugis ‹salaka› 'silver', Alorese ‹salaka› 'silver'.

Likely borrowing from Timorese Austronesian. This Wersing item appears to involve a form {sa-} a reduction of a form like Tetun ‹sabraka› 'orange' plus a form similar to Tetun ‹malae› 'foreign'. Tetun not likely the source here.
Malay ‹sapi› 'cow'.
Alorese sari 'sea wife'.
Malay ‹seng› < Dutch ‹zink› 'zinc'.
Malay ‹sekolah› < Dutch ‹school›.
Malay ‹cina› 'China, Chinese'.
Likely Austronesian, cf. PMP *sudu 'spoon, ladle, scoop' (ACD).
Tetun ‹serbisu› ‘work’ < Portuguese ‹service›.

Pronunciation: ˈski mos ~ səˈki mos ~ siˈki mos

Borrowed_Word: Tokodede Maubara ‹soa› ‘house’ (< *sowa, cf. Tokodede Likisa ‹soba› ‘sitting place made of slatted bamboo, typically placed under a traditional house’; *b > w is regular in Maubara Tokodede).
Central Timorese Austronesian, Tokodede ‹sor›, Kemak ‹sora› 'sew' < PCMP *sora 'sew' (ACD).
Malay ‹susah› 'hardship'.
sèpe < Tetun ‹sapeu› < Portuguese ‹chapéu› 'hat'.
Malay ‹tabe› 'greet', possibly with Timorese Austronesian imtermediate, e.g., Helong ‹tabe› 'greet, respect'.
Likely borrowing given that tamarind was introduced from India (Verheijen 1984:69).

General_Comment: This is a reciprocal kin term whose reference can be clarified by means the expression ol tamu 'child grandparent/child' which exclusively refers to grandchild.

Borrowed_Word: Austronesian, cf. PMP *tuak 'palm wine' (ACD).
Tetun ‹tabaku› < Portuguese ‹tabaco› 'tobacco'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *takaw 'steal' (ACD). This is an early Austronesian borrowing that preserves the diphthong that was lost in most Austronesian languages in area.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *timuR ‘southeast monsoon’ (ACD).

General_Comment: Also found in a small number of fixed combinations.

Borrowed_Word: Austronesian, cf. PMP *buni 'hide, conceal' (ACD). Likely early borrowing.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *qulin 'rudder; steer (a boat)' (ACD). Likely West Timorese Austronesian source, e.g., Helong ‹ulin› 'rudder'.
Austronesian, cf. PMP *qutan 'small, wild herbaceous plants; scrub-land, bush' (ACD). Possible source languages found on all sides of Alor.
Austronesian, cf. PCMP *bayan 'row'. Known reflexes of this are concentrated in SW Maluku, e.g., Kisar ‹wain›, Leti ‹vaːni› 'row'.
Austronesian, PMP *balik ‘reverse, turn around’ (ACD). Certainly a seperate borrowing event from that of -wari 'return, go back'.
